00:01:01.939 --> 00:01:06.899
So for those of you who are new to Xsan, let's
kind of talk a little bit about what it is.

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:08.890
It's a shared file system.

00:01:08.890 --> 00:01:15.180
It's ideal for sharing sharing file content
in a high performance way for video editing,

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:17.950
for servers, for high performance computing.

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:21.280
Kind of anything that needs high
performance access to shared storage.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:23.849
So what does that mean?

00:01:23.849 --> 00:01:27.149
Well, let's kind of take a look at what
a traditional file server looks like.

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:30.660
So traditional file sharing environment,
we have some storage there at the top.

00:01:30.659 --> 00:01:33.619
It's connected to that file server using fibre channel.

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:36.609
Nice big fat pipe between the server and the storage.

00:01:36.609 --> 00:01:42.819
But those clients down there, which are trying very hard
to run Final Cut Pro, are attempting to get to that storage

00:01:42.819 --> 00:01:46.119
over gigabit Ethernet and it's all going through one server.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:50.290
So gigabit Ethernet is half the performance
of even just one fibre channel port

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:52.810
and chances are that server's connected with both.

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:58.740
So what's going to happen is, you might be able to sustain, you
know, a couple of streams of video, but more than likely,

00:01:58.739 --> 00:02:00.989
you're going to have a couple of clients drop frames.

00:02:00.989 --> 00:02:01.769
That's not what you want.

00:02:01.769 --> 00:02:03.700
That makes your whole day bad.

00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:06.240
So if we take a look at Xsan.

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:10.310
So in Xsan, all the clients are
directly attached to the storage.

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:12.729
They all have a nice big fat pipe to the RAID.

00:02:12.729 --> 00:02:15.079
We have something that's very similar to a server.

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:16.810
We call it Xsan Controller.

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:18.259
It kind of hangs off to the side.

00:02:18.259 --> 00:02:19.859
It's connected to the storage as well.

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:24.990
And it is in charge of dealing with all of the metadata
associated with the file systems; so, you know,

00:02:24.990 --> 00:02:28.790
the file names, their owners, their
creation dates, all those things.

00:02:28.789 --> 00:02:32.959
But it is not actually involved in the transfer of the data.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:39.320
So another nice property of Xsan is that the
performance scales when you add storage.

00:02:39.319 --> 00:02:45.180
So in this case, you know, we might have a work load that
requires more bandwidth than just one RAID can provide.

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:49.080
So we add another RAID and the pipes get fatter.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:51.540
And again, you know, we can keep scaling that up.

00:02:51.539 --> 00:02:54.590
You know, add another couple of
RAIDS and the pipes get fatter again.

00:02:54.590 --> 00:03:02.460
Another nice property about Xsan is that you can add a
redundant controller to provide failover capability.

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:08.360
So if you look at the our first file server
slide, there is one server and that's it.

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:10.900
I mean that one server can be connected
to that one set of storage.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:14.020
And if that server goes down, then
all those clients are out of luck.

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:17.909
In Xsan, you can have a redundant
controller, we call it a standby controller.

00:03:17.909 --> 00:03:23.159
So if the primary controller were to fail for
whatever reason, the stand by controller just takes

00:03:23.159 --> 00:03:26.729
over transparently and the clients
can still access the data.

