added pretuned volume workload settings.

00:15:39.950 --> 00:15:45.430
So one of the things that may or may
not be obvious to people in the room is

00:15:45.429 --> 00:15:50.209
that if you have a volume that's
been tuned to stream big video files,

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:52.879
it might not be so great for hosting home directories.

00:15:52.879 --> 00:15:55.200
There's kind of two different ends of the continuum.

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:59.780
Big files that are read sequentially versus small
files that are accessed completely randomly.

00:15:59.779 --> 00:16:05.439
You need to set the volume up differently to work
optimally for those two types of configurations.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:11.690
In the old Admin app you had to know a lot of magic to make
this happen and we've kind of made that a little simpler.

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:19.020
We've we're providing some sort of presets that will
allow you to select kind of at a high level what kind

00:16:19.019 --> 00:16:22.379
of workload you're going to use that volume for.

00:16:22.379 --> 00:16:27.899
It'll pretune a bunch of settings, both on
the controller side and on the client side.

00:16:27.899 --> 00:16:32.629
And this is actually there's a plug in architecture here.

00:16:32.629 --> 00:16:38.309
If you, for example, are a shop that deploys a lot of
Xsan volumes and you know you're going to be adding more,

00:16:38.309 --> 00:16:41.129
it's going to be possible for you to add your configurations.

00:16:41.129 --> 00:16:46.320
It's just going to be a P list to the application
itself and have it appear in that pop up menu.

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:49.210
