lay out the data that are designed to address that.

00:17:21.849 --> 00:17:28.899
And finally we have some more advanced settings for even
finer finer control for you guys to fine tune your volumes.

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:34.420
You're not going to have to edit config files manually
based on what a kbase article says anymore.

00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:36.600
You're going to have some things that
are right there in the application.

00:17:36.599 --> 00:17:42.289
So if you know that you have, you know, a folder that's
going to have a hundred thousand items in it or more,

00:17:42.289 --> 00:17:47.859
it's going to be possible for you to tune up some
settings to make that work a little better.

00:17:47.859 --> 00:17:50.889
So let's take a look at what the new data layout looks like.

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:54.640
First let's look at what the old one looks like,
the kind of standard one that we use today.

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:59.259
And this still exists in the Xsan 2 software.

00:17:59.259 --> 00:18:00.980
So we have two movie clips here.

00:18:00.980 --> 00:18:04.349
They're both uncompressed high def movie
clips that require a lot of throughput.

00:18:04.349 --> 00:18:08.959
Each of them requires, you know, two full
Xserve RAID's worth of bandwidth.

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:12.620
So we have a storage pool here that's going to hold our video.

00:18:12.619 --> 00:18:20.119
And we have that storage pool has an affinity assigned
to it so when people are storing their video files

00:18:20.119 --> 00:18:25.129
in this their video folder, it's
getting steered to this storage pool.

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:29.280
So when we write the first movie, it's
going to get spread across all of those RAIDS.

00:18:29.279 --> 00:18:34.609
When we write the second movie, it's also
going to get spread across all those RAIDS.

00:18:34.609 --> 00:18:40.759
So the problem here is that if you're accessing those two
video streams independently, you're going to have contention.

00:18:40.759 --> 00:18:43.150
Those RAIDS are going to be doing a lot of work.

00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:46.050
The discs inside are actually going to
be seeking back and forth a lot.

00:18:46.049 --> 00:18:50.490
And if you push this too far, you may drop frames.

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:55.440
So what we've done is the new streaming
data layout that is going to be enabled

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.610
when you select the appropriate
volume configuration when you set

00:18:58.609 --> 00:19:03.459
up your volume is we actually split
that up into multiple storage pools.

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:10.559
But your users might be used to having one folder that
has an affinity for video to put their content in.

00:19:10.559 --> 00:19:12.629
They don't want to have to know that
they have to put it in different folders.

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:20.400
What we've done is decoupled storage pools from affinities,
and now affinities can encompass multiple storage pools.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:25.930
So now the user can drag, you know,
a movie file into their video folder

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:28.970
and the first one's going to get written
to the video one storage pool.

00:19:28.970 --> 00:19:31.579
The second one's going to get written
to the video two storage pool.

00:19:31.579 --> 00:19:35.549
They're both going to have the bandwidth they need and
they're not going to have contention for each other's drives

00:19:35.549 --> 00:19:40.950
because we round robin those files
across those storage pools.

00:19:40.950 --> 00:19:46.509
So the third big new thing that we have
in Xsan 2 is something we call MultiSAN,

00:19:46.509 --> 00:19:50.259
and what this allows you to do is
provision your Xsan controllers.

00:19:50.259 --> 00:19:56.720
So I have a diagram coming because this is maybe
a little hard to grasp just from the text here.

00:19:56.720 --> 00:20:00.900
But what this really allows you to do is isolate
your mission critical volumes away from one another.

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:04.430
So if you have something that's really
important, like a playout volume,

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:08.539
you don't want trouble on another
volume interfering with that playout.

00:20:08.539 --> 00:20:12.009
This allows you to do that while
still having global visibility.

00:20:12.009 --> 00:20:19.609
So it allows you to have one machine connected to sort
of both SAN islands to move the data back and forth.

00:20:19.609 --> 00:20:22.189
So let's take a look at a diagram here.

00:20:22.190 --> 00:20:25.700
So over on the left we have a post production volume

00:20:25.700 --> 00:20:30.410
with some Final Cut Pro workstations
and they have their Xsan controllers.

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:33.670
Then over on the right we have a playout volume.

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:38.560
And there's a playout server that's playing
out to air and it's pulling its data directly

00:20:38.559 --> 00:20:43.409
from its volume with its own dedicated controllers.

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:45.350
In between there we actually have a data mover.

00:20:45.349 --> 00:20:46.219
This is optional.

00:20:46.220 --> 00:20:53.650
I wanted to point this out because I think there's a
developer opportunity here for a for a playout server

00:20:53.650 --> 00:21:00.330
that can watch, for example a folder in the production
volume and do a rate limited copy up to the playout volume.

00:21:00.329 --> 00:21:05.269
Using Finder to copy that data you're going to
really pound those discs to try to copy data fast.

00:21:05.269 --> 00:21:08.529
So I think there's a developer
opportunity here in that data mover piece.

00:21:08.529 --> 00:21:12.549
But as you can see here we've got these
two sets of control lists provisioned away.

00:21:12.549 --> 00:21:16.309
So how many of you run multiple
volumes and you have like a pool

00:21:16.309 --> 00:21:19.089
of like four controllers if you in your SAN deployments?

00:21:19.089 --> 00:21:20.029
Let me see a show of hands.

00:21:20.029 --> 00:21:20.639
A few people here.

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:23.980
Okay. So you may have noticed that when you bring

00:21:23.980 --> 00:21:27.509
up the SAN you might have all four volumes
being hosted on one controller, right?

00:21:27.509 --> 00:21:29.549
If you observe that behavior before?

00:21:29.549 --> 00:21:32.250
MultiSAN allows you to sort of fix that problem.

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:36.000
You can say, well these two controllers
are only involved with this volume.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:39.210
These two controllers are only involved with this volume.

00:21:39.210 --> 00:21:44.480
So if you have a failure of a controller
on, say, the production volume,

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:47.940
neither one of the playout controllers is
going to attempt to take control of that volume.

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:51.150
They're completely isolated, but there's
still completely global visibility.

00:21:51.150 --> 00:21:54.460
So everything can see everything else.

