00:33:36.299 --> 00:33:40.809
Now you can imagine in a live sporting event
how important that is because you can't wait

00:33:40.809 --> 00:33:44.819
to for an event to finish before you can start editing.

00:33:44.819 --> 00:33:48.639
Well, the beauty of this is, of course
you can be editing as it's coming in.

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:53.810
They can online and do some color grading,
edit this thing, and send it out right away.

00:33:53.809 --> 00:33:57.599
Extremely successful application and deployment.

00:33:57.599 --> 00:34:02.480
They used it at the World Cup as
did a couple of other broadcasters.

00:34:02.480 --> 00:34:11.510
Another high profile customer of ours around the world
is CCTV, Central China Television in Beijing, China.

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:18.020
And they were launching a television network
that was an HD broadcast facility and they needed

00:34:18.019 --> 00:34:23.360
over 20 Final Cut Pro systems to be
editing multiple shows simultaneously.

00:34:23.360 --> 00:34:26.890
And they turned to Xsan and Final Cut Studio.

00:34:26.889 --> 00:34:31.339
And at that time they really had an issue.

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:35.280
They wanted to work in uncompressed
HD to get the highest quality.

00:34:35.280 --> 00:34:41.680
But as Jason spoke of earlier, you have bandwidth issues.

00:34:41.679 --> 00:34:49.269
High definition, HD, can range from 100 to
about 150 megabytes per second per stream.

00:34:49.269 --> 00:34:53.960
And Final Cut Pro can allow you to edit
multiple streams on a single station.

00:34:53.960 --> 00:34:58.559
So you can see that you do the math and you
are not going to get 20 uncompressed streams here.

00:34:58.559 --> 00:35:05.190
They used the DVC Pro HD codec
primarily in addition to uncompressed.

00:35:05.190 --> 00:35:12.679
Well Final Cut Studio 2 has a new codec
and that codec is called Apple Pro Res 422.

00:35:12.679 --> 00:35:22.129
The beauty of this codec is that it allows you to edit
uncompressed quality at standard definition data rates.

00:35:22.130 --> 00:35:25.530
It's a full raster or a full frame rate codec.

00:35:25.530 --> 00:35:27.990
It's an eight or ten bit codec.

00:35:27.989 --> 00:35:30.000
It's a variable bit rate codec.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:33.809
And it allows you, as I said, to work in very high,

00:35:33.809 --> 00:35:39.659
extremely high quality HD as around
20 to 22 megabytes per second.

00:35:39.659 --> 00:35:44.940
So an incredibly efficient codec and
CCTV is incredibly excited about this.

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:51.909
They will be able to move all of these stations
to this codec for a higher quality output.

00:35:51.909 --> 00:35:56.480
Next, traveling the globe, we're now looking at Televisa.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:36:05.030
